3.1 Source buffers and sidecars
===============================

A source buffer is the Org document being reviewed.  The default local
backend stores comments in a sibling sidecar whose name ends in
‘.comments.org’.  For example, ‘article.org’ uses
‘article.comments.org’.

   Sidecars are ordinary Org files.  Each top-level heading represents a
root comment.  Replies are child headings.  Comment metadata is stored
as Org properties with the ‘ORG_COMMENTS_’ prefix.


File: org-comments.info,  Node: Anchors,  Next: Page comments,  Prev: Source buffers and sidecars,  Up: Concepts

3.2 Anchors
===========

Inline comments store target text and compact position metadata.  When
the source text changes, ‘org-comments’ can report comments as stale or
re-anchor imported inline comments using exact and fuzzy matching.


File: org-comments.info,  Node: Page comments,  Next: Collaboration state,  Prev: Anchors,  Up: Concepts

3.3 Page comments
=================

Page comments are comments about the entire document instead of a
specific text range.  They are represented as footer/page records and
can be shown in a page comments panel.


File: org-comments.info,  Node: Collaboration state,  Prev: Page comments,  Up: Concepts

3.4 Collaboration state
=======================

Backends normalize collaboration metadata into provider-neutral fields:

   • remote identifiers and parent/thread identifiers;
   • remote state such as present, missing, deleted, or unknown;
   • local state such as draft, edited, pending push, or push error;
   • sync state such as clean, dirty, conflict, or error;
   • resolved and actionable state;
   • backend-qualified people identity.

   See also the backend-neutral model in ‘../COLLABORATION.md’.


File: org-comments.info,  Node: Local Org Sidecars,  Next: Comment UI,  Prev: Concepts,  Up: Top

4 Local Org Sidecars
********************

The default backend is ‘org’.  It reads and writes local Org sidecars
and does not require network access.

   New sidecar metadata uses only ‘ORG_COMMENTS_*’ properties.  Legacy
‘HUB_COMMENT_*’ properties are migration input only.  Normal collection
reports legacy sidecars as requiring explicit migration instead of
silently reading the old format.


File: org-comments.info,  Node: Comment UI,  Next: Backends,  Prev: Local Org Sidecars,  Up: Top

5 Comment UI
************

‘org-comments-mode’ is the standalone minor mode and the recommended
activation point for users.  It installs Org-native bindings, and when
‘org-comments-enable-overlays’ is non-nil it also shows overlays for
inline targets and displays page-comment markers.  The default panel is
implemented by ‘org-comments-panel-mode’ and can be replaced or enriched
by setting UI adapter variables.

   The package does not install Evil, leader-key, or layout-specific
bindings.  Personal keybindings belong in user configuration.

   User-facing commands such as ‘org-comments-open-remote’,
‘org-comments-push’, ‘org-comments-reply’, ‘org-comments-pull’,
‘org-comments-sync’, and the mark commands are DWIM: they operate on the
current Org source comment when called from an Org source buffer, and on
the current rendered row/source when called from
‘org-comments-panel-mode’.


File: org-comments.info,  Node: Backends,  Next: Confluence Backend,  Prev: Comment UI,  Up: Top

6 Backends
**********

Backends register a backend id, capabilities, and operation functions
through ‘org-comments-register-backend’.  Generic commands detect the
active backend from the current source buffer and dispatch to the
backend operation.

   Important operations include:

   • list or collect comments;
   • open the remote comment;
   • push local comment edits;
   • pull remote comment state;
   • sync comments.

   Backend ‘:sync’ is comments-only.  It must not perform a full
document or page sync.  Provider packages may offer separate
full-document synchronization commands outside the generic
‘org-comments’ backend contract.

